EPIZOOTIC HEMORRHAGIC DISEASE, CERVIDS - USA (MULTISTATE) (11)
**************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this update:
[1] New York
[2] Delaware

******
[1] New York
Date: Fri 12 Oct 2007
Source: Poughkeepsie Journal, Associated Press report [edited]
<http://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071012/NEWS01/71012042>


State conservation officials are asking deer hunters heading out for
the start of bow hunting season Saturday [13 Oct 2007] in the state's
southern zone to report any sick, dying or dead animals as part of an
investigation into whether a disease has reached New York.

The state Department of Environmental Conservation (DEC) said
preliminary tests on 2 of about 20 deer found dead this week around
Voorheesville in southern Albany County indicate that they may have
died of epizootic hemorrhagic disease, or EHD. Samples are pending
with national laboratories for confirmation. They would the 1st
confirmed cases in New York state.

The disease -- which doesn't pose a known threat to human health --
causes hemorrhaging and has mostly afflicted white-tailed deer in the
southeast, the DEC said. It was reported in mid-Atlantic states this
summer [2007], is transmitted by certain types of biting flies in
late summer and fall, and subsides as weather turns cold and the
flies die.

Officials are still waiting for test results from 2 other
laboratories but say if the deer did die from EHD, it would be the
1st time the disease has been found in the state. The deer are also
being tested for rabies, chronic wasting disease, and possible
poisoning, the agency said.

--
