******
[2] Delaware
Date: Fri 12 Oct 2007
Source: The News Journal, Delaware [edited]
<http://www.delawareonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071012/NEWS/71012027>


An insect-borne disease that has been killing white-tailed deer
throughout North America cannot be contracted by humans and is not a
significant threat to the state's deer herd, state environmental
officials said.

Epizootic hemorrhagic disease, which causes hemorrhaging and
typically kills deer that contract it within 5 days, is transmitted
by small insects called midges, the Department of Natural Resources
and Environmental Control's (DNREC) Division of Fish and Wildlife
said.

Humans can't contract the disease, DNREC said, although they should
avoid consuming the meat of deer that appear visibly sick, due to the
risk of a secondary infection that could be harmful to humans.

At least 75 deer in Delaware have died from the disease, and deer in
neighboring states have fared worse; in Pennsylvania, several
thousand deer have died, DNREC said.

Pesticides can't be used to kill the flies that cause the disease,
nor can deer be vaccinated against it. "We are in a position of
allowing nature to run its course and waiting for a hard frost to
kill the midges," said Joe Rogerson, a Division of Fish and Wildlife
game mammal biologist.

Anyone who encounters a deer carcass whose cause of death is not
apparent should contact Rogerson at 735-3600; the division is
attempting to document deer mortality for future references to the
disease.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[New York and Delaware are reasonably far north to be finding the
disease this late in the season, although many areas have been seeing
seasonal heat waves and frost has not occurred in many areas where it
normally would have been seen by this time of the year. New York is
large enough, and with Pennsylvania as its neighbor, it is not
uncommon to expect the disease in this state. Nonetheless, it is
rather late in the year to be finding it.

A map of the US may be found at
<http://www.nationsonline.org/maps/USA.jpg>.
Both states are in the northeast portion of the country. - Mod.TG]
